2.2 Gini importance in random forest

single tree gini importance .

Single tree \[ \begin{align*} &VI_i = \sum_{n \in t, i_n = i} p(n) \boldsymbol{\Delta}_{gini}(n), \\ &i_n : \text{Sum over all nodes of the tree that use feature i} \\ &p(n) : \text{Probability of using that node for a sample data point} \\ &\boldsymbol{\Delta}_{gini}(n) : \text{Change in gini impurity at that node} \end{align*} \]

feature gini importance feature gini impurity .

\(X_1\), \(X_2\) gini importance .

gini impurity , feature importance \(\boldsymbol{\Delta_{gini}}\) .

\(\boldsymbol{\Delta_{gini}}\) \(X_1\) gini impurity split gini impurity . split gini impurity gini impurity . \(X_1\) \(\boldsymbol{\Delta_{gini}}\) 0.26 .

2.3 Purmutation importance in random forest

gini importance gini impurity feature importance . purmutation importance gini importance gini .

( )

\[ \begin{align*} \text{within each tree } t \\ &VI^{(t)}(x_j) = \frac{\sum_{i=\bar B^{(t)}} I(y_i = \hat{y}_i^{(t)})}{|\bar B^{(t)}|} - \frac{\sum_{i=\bar B^{(t)}} I(y_i = \hat{y}_{i, \pi_j}^{(t)})}{|\bar B^{(t)}|} \\ &\hat{y}_i^{(t)} = f^{(t)}(x_i) : \text{predicted class before permuting} \\ &\hat{y}_{i, \pi_j}^{(t)} = f^{(t)}(x_{i, \pi_j}) : \text{predicted class after permuting }X_j \\ &X_{i, \pi_j} = (x_{i,1}, \cdots, x_{i, j-1}, x_{\pi_j(i), j}, x_{i, j+1}, \cdots , x_{i, p}) \\ & \bar B^{(t)} = \text{out of bag sample} \\ \text{over all trees:} \\ &\text{1. row importance : } VI(x_j) = \frac{\sum_{t = 1}^{ntree}VI^{(t)}(x_j)}{ntree} \\ &\text{2. scale importance : } sVI(x_j) = \frac{VI(x_j)}{\frac{\hat{\sigma}}{\sqrt ntree}} \\ \end{align*} \] tree \(t=1\) \(\sum_{i = B} I(y_i = \hat{y_i})\) \(\sum_{i = B} I(y_i = \hat{y_i, \pi_j})\) feature importance , tree feature importance random forest feature importance . purmutation . feature importance target variable shuffling . shuffling shuffling (permutation ).

https://www.zeileis.org/papers/Lifestat-2008.pdf

R code

set_engine permutation or impurity .

data("ames")
ames_train <- ames %>%
    transmute(Sale_Price = log10(Sale_Price),
              Gr_Liv_Area = as.numeric(Gr_Liv_Area),
              Year_Built, Bldg_Type)

rf_model <- 
    rand_forest(trees = 1000) %>% 
    set_engine("ranger", importance = 'impurity') %>% 
    set_mode("regression")

rf_wflow <- 
    workflow() %>% 
    add_formula(
        Sale_Price ~ Gr_Liv_Area + Year_Built + Bldg_Type) %>% 
    add_model(rf_model) 

rf_fit <- rf_wflow %>% fit(data = ames_train)

rf_fit %>% 
  extract_fit_parsnip()

shapley value .

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9haIOplEIGM&t=152s

feature , Game Black box , Payout prediction . shapley value feature , . marginal contribution , feature marginal contribution shapley value .

process

\[ \begin{align*} \phi_j(val) &= \sum_{S \subseteq\{x_1, \cdots, x_p\}\setminus \{x_j\}} \frac{|S|!(P-|S|-1)!}{p!}(val(S \cup\{x_j\})-val(S)) \\ &S : \text{subset of the features} \\ &p : \text{the number of features} \\ &x : \text{the vector of feature values of instance to be explained} \\ &val : \text{prediction for feature values} \end{align*} \]

shapley value .

Example

kaggle competition kaggle competition 3 player . player .

\[ \begin{align*} &val(1) = 100, \, val(2) = 125, \, val(3) = 50, \\ &val(1, 2) = 270, \, val(1, 3) = 375, \, val(2, 3) = 350, \\ &\, val(1, 2, 3) = 500 \end{align*} \]

, 3 player 500$ , 1 player 100$, 2 player 125$, 1 2 player 270$ .. etc ( ML model val prediction value ).

player marginal contribution table .

http://faculty.econ.ucdavis.edu/faculty/bonanno/teaching/122/Shapley.pdf

\(\phi_2(val)\)(2s expected marginal contribution) : \(\frac{1}{6}(170+125+125+125+125+300)=\frac{970}{6}\)

1s, 2s, 3s expected marginal contribution 500 , \(val(1,2,3)\) .
